1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 (6... Na6 {is a
possible deviation for black. My suggestion here is 7.Bf4, but for more
details, please take a look at game 2.}) 7. d5 {This move marks the beginning
of the Petrosian system. The position in the centre is stable and now the
plans are clear - White is planning to organize a pawn expansion on the
queenside, whereas black is going to undertake an active actions on the
kingside. The battle is very complex and every single move is of a great
importance.} a5 {his is the main and most popular continuation. Black's idea
is to slow down White's queenside pawns. At the same time, in such kind of
positions, the idea to generate pressure on the "e4" open by the manoeuvre
Na6-c5 is an option. However, the move 7...a5 is not the only choice for black.
Let's have a look at his other possibilities.} (7... Nbd7 {Here, my preference
is for the move} 8. Be3 $1 {- Game 3.} (8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5)) (7...
Na6 {is another move which leads to unpleasant positions for Black after} 8.
Nd2 $1 {Delchev-Hamdouchi, 2011 (Game 4)}) 8. Bg5 {In such kind of positions.
White develops his queenside attack in the following way - Nd2, a2-a3, b2-b4,
c4-c5 followed by Nc4. However, if White plays 8.Nd2, then the bishop on "c1"
will be out of play. That's why we should develop our bishop, before making
knight manoeuvres.} h6 $1 {Black has no alternatives here, because after} (8...
Na6 {White could play} 9. Nd2 {with an excellent position. Everything is ready
for the execution of the above-mentioned plan.}) 9. Be3 $1 {I have always been
interested in this continuation which leads to very sharp play with mutual
chances. In this variation, Black is under pressure and very often must find
only moves, in order to survive.} ({More positional way to continue is the
main line} 9. Bh4 Na6 10. a3 Bd7 11. Rb1 Qe8 12. b3 Nh7 {With mutual chances.})
9... Ng4 $1 {Again, the best move. Black is planning to realize the f7-f5 pawn
break as soon as possible. As the reader probably knows, this move is the
cornerstone of Black's strategy in King's Indian Defence.} ({In case of} 9...
Nh5 {White can give preference to the calm move} 10. g3 {Black has no
counterplay at all. The move f7-f5 is hardly possible, because after an
eventual exchange on "f5", the knight on "h5" will be hanging. In some cases,
by means of the typical Nh4, White could radically stop Black's counterplay on
the kingside. On the other hand, our queenside play will be developing
progressively.}) 10. Bd2 f5 {There are is nothing more logical than this move.}
11. h3 Nf6 {At first sight, White's play is not very consistent, because he
has allowed Black to realize f7-f5 break with a tempo. Then, what is the real
intention of Vladimir Kramnik - one of the most successful anti-King's Indian
players?} 12. exf5 gxf5 (12... Bxf5 {is a typical mistake.} 13. g4 Bd7 14. Qc1
g5 15. h4 {With a dangerous attack.}) 13. Qc1 {A very deep idea prepared in
Kramnik's home analysis. White wants to provoke the move 13...Kh7. In a lot of
variation, on "h7" square, the black king will be under the fire of White's
pieces. Is White's idea a serious try to get an advantage or just an opening
experiment? In my analysis, I will try to give an appropriate answer to these
questions. In all cases, however, this novelty is highly effective. When it
comes to a practical game, even for a top player like Nakamura is difficult to
get through the opponents home preparations.} f4 {By playing this creative
move, Nakamura tries to deviate from the home preparations of his opponent.} ({
Of course, the most natural move is} 13... Kh7 {The reason why Nakamura
doesn't go for this obvious move is quite simple - there are is no doubt that
13...Kh7 is the most extensively analysed continuation by Kramnik.} 14. g4 {
The attack begins. Let's have a look at Black's different options. Na6 This is
probably the best defence. Maybe, if we go deeper into the analysis of this
position, we will reach the conclusion that Black's play is quite satisfactory.
For the moment, however, I would like to share with you some original
attacking ideas.} Na6 ({After} 14... fxg4 15. hxg4 Nxg4 (15... Bxg4 16. Bxh6)
16. Ng5+ Kg8 17. Nge4 {White's attack is decisive. For example -} Qe7 18. f3
Nf6 19. Bxh6 {with a winning position.}) ({Black can't solve his problems by} 
14... e4 {because white can occupy the central "d4" square and Black's
position will start to ruin. As an example, I give the following variation:}
15. Nd4 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd4 17. Bxh6 Bxf2+ (17... Rg8 18. Qd2 Nc6 19. O-O-O $18)
18. Kxf2 Qh4+ 19. Kg2 Qxh6 20. Qxh6+ Kxh6 21. Nxc7 $16 {Despite of the
material equality, White has a huge advantage, because of the better
development of his pieces.}) ({The attempt to close the center by means of} 
14... f4 {doesn't work either, because after} 15. Qc2+ Kg8 {White has at his
disposal an effective pawn break -} 16. g5 hxg5 (16... Nh5 17. Qg6) 17. Nxg5
Qe7 18. O-O-O {The open "g"file makes the attack unstoppable.}) 15. g5 hxg5 16.
Bxg5 {We have reached one of the important crossroads in this variation. Black
is ahead in development and has a pawn majority in the center. Even though,
his king is vulnerable. After some logical moves like Qc2, 0-0-0 and Rg1,
White can generate unpleasant threats against Black's king.} Qe8 (16... Rg8 17.
Qc2 Qf8 18. Rg1 Kh8 19. O-O-O Nb4 20. Qd2 Ne4 21. Nxe4 fxe4 22. Nh4 Bf6 23. a3
$16) 17. Rg1 {In White's favour are the complications arising after the move:
e4 I bring to your attention the following forced line -} e4 ({The move} 17...
f4 {loses on the spot, because of the weakened "b1 - h7"diagonal.} 18. Qb1+ Kh8
(18... Kg8 19. Bh6) (18... e4 19. Bxf4) 19. Nh4 $18) ({The centralization of
the knight looks more logical, however, even in that case, White retains a
considerable pressure.} 17... Nc5 18. Be3 $1 {A typical idea! Now White is
ready to occupy the "g5"square with the knight.} Nce4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Qc2 Bf6
21. h4 Rg8 22. O-O-O $40) 18. Nd4 Nc5 19. Qf4 {Of course! The queen should be
transferred to the kingside.} Nd3+ 20. Bxd3 exd3+ 21. Kd2 Ne4+ 22. Kxd3 Nxc3
23. Qh4+ Kg8 24. Ne6 Bxe6 25. Bh6 Rf7 26. Bxg7 Rxg7 27. Rxg7+ Kxg7 28. Rg1+ {
With a mate to follow.}) ({Without doubt, the principled way to approach the
position is the move} 13... e4 {Black gains space in the center and his plan
is to make use of the fact that he is ahead in development. The drawback of
the move 13...e4 is the weakness of the "f4" square, where white can install
his knight.} 14. Nh4 $1 Kh7 (14... Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxh4 16. Nxc7) 15. g3 $1 (15.
g4 Nxd5 $13) 15... Na6 16. Ng2 Nc5 17. Nf4 Nfd7 18. Be3 Ne5 19. Qd1 {White's
position remain more pleasant. His plan includes the manoeuvre Kf1-g2 followed
by play on the kingside.}) 14. g3 $1 {A principled choice. Probably Kramnik is
still playing according to his analysis. Now, we enter a phase where a huge
complications are about to arise. The question is who will be the first to
reach the opponent's king.} e4 15. Nh4 e3 {There is no choice left. After
making a sequence of precise moves, Black is still in the game.} ({It would be
a mistake to play} 15... f3 $2 {because of} 16. Bd1 $1 {White's bishop is
immediately transferred to the "b1 - h7" diagonal.} Kh7 17. Bc2 Na6 (17... Qe7
18. O-O $1 Na6 19. Re1 Nc5 20. Be3 $18 {Black is no longer able to protect his
central pawn.}) 18. Be3 Qe7 19. Nxf3 $16) 16. fxe3 fxg3 (16... fxe3 17. Bxe3)
17. Ng6 Rf7 $6 {First, but quite a serious mistake by Nakamura. Here, the
choice was between 17...g2 and 17...Re8! . In my analysis, I will provide you
with some points of reference that will help you to orientate yourself in the
tremendous complications that will arise soon.} ({The natural move} 17... g2 {
turns out to be weaker. Here, I come with the following forced sequence:} 18.
Rg1 Bxh3 19. Nxf8 Qxf8 20. Qc2 {White's plan is very clear - he will castle
long and will try to invade the opponent's camp by means of Qg6. As it will be
clearly demonstrated by my analysis, the strong passer on "g2" doesn't
compensate the weakness of Black's king and the missing exchange.} Nbd7 (20...
Ng4 21. O-O-O Nf2 22. Qg6 $1 {White is ready to give the exchange back, as his
only idea is to transfer the light-squared bishop to the "b1 - h7"diagonal.}
Na6 (22... Nxd1 23. Nxd1) 23. Be1 $1 Nxd1 24. Nxd1 Nc5 (24... Qf6 25. Qg3) 25.
Bc3 Qf7 26. Qg3 {White is going to eliminate the "g2"pawn and his attack will
be decisive.}) 21. Qg6 Ng4 (21... Ne5 22. Qg3) 22. O-O-O Nde5 23. Qh5 Nf2 24.
Be1 Nfd3+ (24... Bg4 25. Bxg4 Nfxg4 26. Qh3) 25. Kb1 Bf5 26. Ka1 Nb4 27. Rd2 {
White has parried all the direct threats and it seems that Black's
compensation for the exchange is not sufficient. Also, it's not clear if the
"g2" pawn will survive.}) ({Black's best try is} 17... Re8 $1 {By occupying
the semi-open "e" file, black rook creates a dangerous opposition with the
white king.} 18. Nf4 $1 {Very important move. From "f4" the knight not only
stops the advance of the "g" pawn, but at the same time, under favourable
circumstances, could enter the attack via "h5" or "e6". In this position,
black has two main options at his disposal, but non of them manages to solve
their problems. Of course, further practical tests are required.} Na6 (18...
Ne4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. Rg1 $1 {The "g3" pawn is the last Black's fortress.
That's why we should eliminate it as soon as possible.} Qh4 21. Kd1 $1 Na6 (
21... Bxh3 22. Be1) (21... Re5 22. Qc2 Na6 23. Qg6 Bf5 24. Qxg3 Qxg3 25. Rxg3
Kh7 26. Bc3 Re7 27. Bxg7 Rxg7 28. Rxg7+ Kxg7 29. Bg4 $16) 22. Be1) 19. Qb1 $1 {
Again, White threatens to invade via "g6".} Nc5 20. Qg6 Re5 21. h4 {A
necessary move - the threat of Rg5 must be parried.} Nce4 (21... Bf5 22. Qxg3 {
Now the "g" file is open and black king is in a great danger.} Nfe4 23. Nxe4
Nxe4 24. Qg2 Nxd2 25. Nh5 Qe7 26. Rg1 {With a decisive attack.}) ({The move} 
21... Nfe4 {doesn't help either -} 22. Nh5 Qe7 23. Nxg3 $16) 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23.
Nh5 Rxh5 {After this move, I don't think that black has any compensation for
the sacrificed exchange.} ({He should have given preference to} 23... Qe7 {
and after the forced sequence} 24. Nxg7 Qxg7 25. Qxg7+ Kxg7 26. Rg1 Bf5 27. Bc3
Nxc3 28. Rxg3+ Kf6 29. bxc3 c6 {We reach an ending, despite of being a pawn up,
White can't win easily.}) 24. Bxh5 Qe7 25. Rg1 {Followed by 26. Bf3. Black's
position is lost.}) 18. Qc2 {Very important move. Before starting to attack
the "g3" pawn, we should prevent the move 18...Bf5.} (18. Rg1 Bf5 19. Rxg3 Na6)
18... Nfd7 $2 {By making a move with an already developed piece, Black is
wasting time. However, his desire to exchange the strong "Ng6" is
understandable. I think that he should have given preference to the
development of the queen's knight.} ({The naive} 18... g2 $2 {leads to a
difficult position after:} 19. Rg1 Bxh3 20. O-O-O {With the idea of 21.Nf4.}) (
{The other knight move doesn't pose any problems either:} 18... Nh7 19. O-O-O
Na6 20. Nf4 Bf5 21. e4 Nb4 22. Qb1 Bd7 23. Rdg1 {The "g3" pawn is going to
fall.}) ({Without doubt, Black's best is} 18... Na6 $1 19. Nf4 Nc5 $1 {A
precise move! In such kind of positions, it's very important to control the
"e4" square.} (19... Nb4 20. Qg6 Nh7 21. O-O) 20. O-O-O ({The standard} 20. Qg6
{could be met by} Nfe4 $1 21. Nxe4 Bf5) 20... Nfe4 $1 {Nevertheless! Now white
is forced to enter the following line:} 21. Nxe4 Bf5 22. Bf3 Qe7 23. Ne6 Bh7
24. Rdf1 (24. Bg2 Rf2 $1) 24... Raf8 25. Nxf8 Rxf8 26. Bg2 Nxe4 27. Rxf8+ Bxf8
$13 {Black has definitely some compensation for the exchange, but it's
difficult to say if it's enough. A complicated battle with mutual chances is
to follow.}) 19. O-O-O {White king has managed to escape. Now, after the
elimination of the "g3" pawn, White' attack is going to be unstoppable.} Ne5
20. Rhf1 {After the exchange of the rooks, black king will run out of
defenders.} (20. Nf4 $1 {is probably even better} Na6 (20... Bf5 21. e4 Bc8 22.
Rdg1) 21. Rhg1 Nb4 22. Qb1 Qh4 23. Be1 Bf5 24. Bxg3) 20... Rxf1 21. Rxf1 Bxh3 (
21... Nbd7 22. Rg1 Qg5 23. Nxe5 Bxe5 24. Ne4 Qg7 25. Bc3) 22. Rg1 {Now, the
game is over.} Qf6 (22... g2 23. Nf4) 23. Rxg3 (23. Nf4 Bf5 24. e4 Bh7 25. Rxg3
) 23... Nxg6 24. Rxg6 Qf7 25. Rg3 Bf5 26. e4 Bg6 27. Bg4 Qf1+ 28. Nd1 Be5 29.
Bh3 Qf6 30. Rg1 Kh7 31. Bf5 Bxf5 32. exf5 Nd7 {Only now, Nakamura manages to
bring his knight into the play.} 33. Rg6 Qf7 34. Rxh6+ Kg8 35. Rg6+ Kf8 36. Nf2
b5 37. Ng4 bxc4 38. Qxc4 Qxf5 39. Rg8+ Ke7 40. Bg5+ Bf6 41. Qe2+ {A great
achievement by Kramnik! In general, we are used to see Nakamura winning his
games in this style. After the mistakes on moves 17 and 18 ( Rf7 instead of
Re8 and Nfd7 instead of Na6 ), white has managed to organize an overwhelming
attack.} 1-0

