1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 Na6 {One of the ideas
behind this move order is to avoid the Petrosian system. On the other hand,
Black's plan is to realize the e7-e5 advance, intending to meet the move d4-d5
by Nc5.} (6... e5 7. d5) 7. Bf4 $1 {A very original move which is directed
against the central break e7-e5. As we are going to see later, White's
dark-squared bishop is perfectly located for a transition into a Benoni pawn
structure, which can arise after the move c7-c5.} Nh5 $1 {This is the main
line.} ({After} 7... c5 $6 8. d5 {we transpose into a favourable version of
the Averbakh system. As a rule, in such kind of positions, Black's counterplay
is usually connected with e7-e6 and b7-b5 pawn breaks. The first of these
ideas is impossible due to the strong "Bf4", while the queenside counterplay
could be easily stopped by means of a2-a4. Black, at his turn, is planning to
play in the center, once his pieces are developed in the optimal way. In that
vein, in the future, we should consider the central pawn break e4-e5. Here, I
provide an example of how the game could continue.} Nc7 (8... Nh5 9. Bg5 $1 {
An important intermediate move. Before going to it's typical "e3" square, the
light-squared bishop is trying to provoke the weakening h7-h6 advance.} h6 10.
Be3 e5 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Qd2 Kh7 13. Rd1 {White has a clear advantage - black
knights are out of play and "d6" pawn is a serious weakness.}) 9. h3 $1 {
Very useful and typical move for such set-ups. White not only makes a room for
his dark-squared bishop, but at the same time prevents the possible exchanges
that could arise after 9...Bg4. According to one of the main rules in chess,
we shouldn't exchange pieces, when we have a space advantage.} a6 10. a4 Rb8
11. O-O Bd7 12. e5 $1 {Everything is ready for this central break.} Nfe8 13. a5
$1 {An important move in White's strategy. Now, if Black goes for a pawn break
on the queenside, the "a6" pawn will be a weakness until the end of the game.}
b5 14. axb6 Rxb6 15. b3 h6 16. Re1 e6 17. Rc1 $16 {White enjoys a full
domination over the board. Hort,V -Malis,J /Trinec 1972.}) ({The attempt to
prepare the e7-e5 advance by} 7... Nd7 $6 {is too slow. White can develop a
dangerous initiative on the kingside.} 8. Qd2 e5 9. Bh6 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Qf6 11.
O-O-O {And the attack is very strong.} Re8 (11... exd4 12. Nxd4 Ndc5 13. h4 Ne6
14. Nf5 {White's advantage is already decisive. The threat of 15.Nd5 can't be
parried without material loses.} c6 15. h5 $18 Qg5+ 16. Qxg5 Nxg5 17. Nxd6 $18
{Franco Ocampos,Z -Cacho Reigadas,S /Havana 2002/}) 12. c5 $3 {A brilliant
idea which is quite typical for such kind of structures. The threat is 13.Nd5,
followed by Ba6.} exd4 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Nxd4 $18 {White is
winning.}) ({The early development of the light-squared bishop seems to be
premature.} 7... Bg4 {It's obvious that when white bishop is on "f4" Black is
going to attack the center by means of c7-c5. In this vein, if Black goes for
the exchange of his light-squared bishop, his queenside counterplay based on
the b7-b5 advance will be impossible. Also, in a long-term, White's bishop
pair shouldn't be underestimated.} 8. O-O $1 c5 ({In case of} 8... Nd7 {
Again, white should try to weaken Black's kingside by the typical} 9. Bg5 h6
10. Be3 e5 11. d5 f5 12. h3 {Drawbacks of 7.Bg4 become clear. As we know, in
King's Indian defence, Black's basic idea is to launch a kingside attack.
Normally, his attack develops according to the following scenario: f7-f5-f4,
g6-g5-g4-g3 and etc. As a rule, this pawn storm is strongly supported by "Bc8".
After the exchange of this bishop, however, the idea of g5-g4 becomes
impossible to carry out and the attack is unsuccessful.} Bh5 13. Rb1 {After}
Nac5 {I provide a long forced variation at the end of which White's advantage
is out of question.} 14. exf5 gxf5 15. b4 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 e4 17. bxc5 Bxc3 18.
Bxh6 Bg7 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Bxe4 fxe4 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Rxb7 Rf7
24. Qe6 Qe7 25. Re1 $16) 9. d5 Nc7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 {A typical Benoni
structure has arisen. As I have already explained, Black has ran out of
counterplay, because b7-b5 and e7-e6 pawn breaks are impossible. Black is
doomed to passivity.} Nd7 12. Be2 {An important move! From "e2" the bishop not
only controls the "b5", but at the same time makes room for the advance of "f"
pawn.} Ne5 13. Bg5 {The idea is f2-f4.} h6 14. Bh4 g5 {Black is doing
everything in order not to allow the f2-f4 pawn advance. Now, however, the
kingside is too weak. I suggest that you have a look at the game between the
Armenian grandmasters Sargisian and Minasian played in 2005.} 15. Bg3 e6 16.
Bh2 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Qb6 19. b3 Rae8 20. Rad1 Re6 21. Bh5 Qc6 22.
Qxc6 bxc6 23. Rd2 $16 {White has a huge advantage due to his bishop pair an
the weak "d6" pawn. 1-0 Sargissian,G (2630) -Minasian,A (2597)/Yerevan 2005/
CBM 1-132 (66)}) 8. Bg5 $1 {Once again, we come across this typical motif.} h6
({After} 8... Qe8 9. O-O e5 {White is not obliged to clarify the situation in
the center.} 10. Re1 h6 11. Be3 Nf6 12. h3 exd4 13. Bxd4 $1 {White's pieces
are much more active and the opposition along the "e" file is quite annoying
for Black.}) 9. Be3 e5 10. Qd2 (10. g3 {An interesting move which often
transposes to the Petrosian system after} Nf6 11. d5 Ng4 12. Bd2 c6 (12... f5
13. Nh4 $1) 13. h3 Nf6 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Nd2 {In this position, White has an
edge, but compared to the main line, Black is a few tempos ahead. Moreover,
the move g3 has considerably weaken the kingside. Zvjaginsev,V-Tkachiev,V/Biel
1995.}) 10... Nf4 {A necessary sacrifice. Otherwise, White's initiative is
rather annoying.} (10... g5 $5 11. h4 (11. O-O-O Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. h4 g4
14. Ne1) 11... g4 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. O-O-O Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Nf4 15. Bf1 Ne6 16.
Nb3 b6 17. f3 gxf3 18. gxf3 $14) (10... Kh7 11. O-O-O) 11. Bxf4 $1 exf4 12.
Qxf4 g5 (12... c5 13. Qd2 Bg4 14. O-O Bxf3 15. Bxf3 cxd4 16. Nb5) 13. Qe3 c5
14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nd4 Re8 16. O-O Bd7 (16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 f5 18. Bf3 g4 19.
Nf6+ Bxf6 20. Bd5+ Kg7 21. Qd3 Bxd4 22. Qxd4+ Qf6 23. Qd2 Be6 24. f3 $40) 17.
Rad1 {Black's compensation is insufficient - his kingside is weakened and the
"d6" pawn is an weakness.} *

