1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. d5 Nbd7 {
Here, I give preference to} (7... Na6 8. Nd2 $1 {- see the next game.}) 8. Be3
$1 {The most flexible move. White prepares the typical Nd2 with a play on the
queenside to follow. Of course, "g4" square remains unprotected and black may
try to make use of it by attacking the bishop on "e3".} (8. Bg5 {Kramnik -
Kasparov, 1994 Linares.}) 8... Ng4 {The only logical move.} (8... Nc5 9. Nd2 a5
10. a3 {We have reached the position White was aiming for - now he plans to
grab the initiative by playing b2-b4.} Ne8 ({White's play is very easy after a
quiet moves like} 10... Bd7 {For example:} 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Na6 13. Rb1 {
Now, the knight is out of play.} c6 14. O-O cxd5 15. cxd5 Nc7 16. b5 {White's
advantage is obvious. Later, he will follow up with the natural Nc4 Wojtaszek,
R -Fier,A Dubai UAE 2014.}) 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 Na6 14. Qa3 $1 {
A typical move for this line! From "a3" the queen protects the "b4" pawn and
at the same time prepares the c4-c5 advance. Black's kingside counterplay
doesn't seem to be sufficient.} f5 15. O-O f4 16. Ba7 $1 {When a pair of rooks
is exchanged, "a7" become a suitable square for our bishop.} g5 17. f3 Rf6 18.
c5 {The "a6" knight is in a huge danger - the threat is c5-c6. Stocek,J
-Moradiabadi,E Thessaloniki 2007.}) (8... a5 9. Nd2 {White has arranged his
pieces in the optimal way for this set-up. Now, he is planning to advance his
queenside pawns. Without wasting any time, Black must try to generate some
counterplay on the opposite side.} Ne8 10. g4 $1 {In a number of King's Indian
lines, this is a prophylactic rather than an attacking move. Black's idea is
to prevent the move 10...f7-f5 which will be answered by a double exchanged on
"f5" followed by the knight occupation of the "e4" square. Later, white could
continue reducing Black's attacking resources by gaining space on the kingside
( h2-h4-h5).} Nc5 11. h4 f5 12. gxf5 gxf5 13. h5 $1 {If the white pawn was
still on "h2", instead of "h5", Black would have had the move Qh4 at his
disposal.} Kh8 (13... h6 14. Qc2) 14. Qc2 Bf6 {With the idea to trade the
dark-squared bishops.} 15. Rg1 Ne6 ({After} 15... f4 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. O-O-O
Nd6 18. Bg4 {White exchanges opponents most active piece ( Bc8 ). After such
an exchange, Black has no counterplay at all.}) 16. dxe6 f4 17. Bxf4 exf4 18.
Bg4 {White's advantage is obvious. Taking the "e6" pawn is not as easy as it
may seem. Under favourable circumstances, White has the possibility to play
Nd5. Krasenkow,M -Nataf,I Belfort 2012.}) ({doesn't change much.} 8... Nh5 9.
g3 $1 {We shouldn't allow the black knight to jump on "f4".} Nc5 10. Nd2 Nf6
11. g4 $1 {This motif is already familiar to us.} Ne8 12. Rg1 Kh8 13. Qc2 f5
14. gxf5 gxf5 15. O-O-O {With an advantage. Narciso Dublan,M -Diaz Rodriguez,J
Navalmoral 2012.}) 9. Bg5 ({The move} 9. Bd2 {s only a transposition. A
possible continuation is} f5 {White immediately makes use of one of the
drawback's of 7...Nbd7 - the weak "e6" square.} 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Ng5 $1 Nc5
12. O-O {Once the development completed, White is ready to start chasing the
"c5" knight by means of b2-b4. Black must stop this advance.} a5 13. Na4 $1 {
A solid positional approach. After the elimination of the "c5" knight, White
will have better control on the central squares. Moreover, in some variations,
black center is hanging.} Nxa4 14. Qxa4 Qe7 ({White's idea becomes clear in
the following variation:} 14... Bh6 15. Bxg4 fxg4 (15... Bxg5 16. f4) 16. Ne6
Bxe6 17. Bxh6 Bd7 18. Qb3 Rf7 19. f4 gxf3 20. Rxf3 {Position remains unclear,
but black king is vulnerable. We know, that in position with opposite-coloured
bishops, there are a lot of mating possibilities.}) 15. Rae1 Bh6 16. f4 {
After this typical move, Black's position is problematic. Their position is
not stable enough, while there are no chances to launch a kingside attack.
Also, the opposition along the "e"file is quite annoying.}) 9... f6 10. Bd2 a5
({Remember that in positions where White hadn't castled yet, the move} 10...
Nh6 $6 {is not advisable, because the march of "h" pawn can be extremely
dangerous. Here is an example:} 11. h4 $1 a5 ({Impossible is} 11... f5 {
because of} 12. h5 f4 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. Nh4 $1 {The "g6" pawn can't be
protected in a comfortable way. In case of} Qf6 {White plays} ({or} 14... Qe8)
15. Nb5) 12. Qc1 Nf7 13. h5 g5 14. g4 Nc5 15. Nh2 Bd7 16. f3 $16 {Black is
strategically lost. The kingside is completely lost and white has a free hand
on the queenside.}) ({After} 10... f5 11. exf5 gxf5 12. Ng5 Nc5 13. O-O {
we transpose to a variation that was already explained above.}) 11. h3 Nh6 12.
h4 $1 {White realizes the same idea.} Nc5 (12... f5 13. h5 f4 14. hxg6 hxg6 15.
Qc2 {White's advantage is obvious. Later, he can even go for a kingside attack
by playing moves like 0-0-0, Rdg1 followed by g2-g3.}) 13. h5 g5 14. Be3 g4 $6
{An instructive positional mistake. White knight shouldn't be allowed to
occupy the important "h4" square.} ({White retains his advantage even in case
of} 14... b6 {The game could continue in the following way:} 15. Qd2 {A
multi-purpose move. White has two main ideas in this position - castle long
and close the kingside by means of Nh2 with the idea of g2-g4.} Ng4 (15... Bd7
16. Nh2) (15... Nf7 16. O-O-O) 16. h6 $1 {An excellent tactical resource!} Nxh6
(16... Bxh6 17. Nxe5 $1) 17. Nxg5 $16) 15. Nh4 f5 16. exf5 $1 Nxf5 17. Nxf5
Bxf5 18. h6 Bf6 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. Bxg4 {In this position, the play could have
continued:} e4 21. Bxf5 Bxc3+ 22. bxc3 Rxf5 23. Qg4+ Rg5 24. Qe6+ Kh8 25. Rh3
